AB  - Reply by the current authors to the comments made by Claudia Marino (see record 2018-35250-001) on the original article. We thank Dr. Marino for her letter, with which we partially agree and partially disagree. First, we agree that other factors may also play a role in the rise in depression among adolescents after 2011. Indeed, as we have argued elsewhere (e.g., Twenge, 2017), the increase in digital-media use may be more of an indirect (rather than direct) cause of the increase in depression, in that it is the most likely explanation for the decline in face-to-face social interaction (Twenge & Campbell, 2018) and the decline in sleep time over this same time period (Twenge, Krizan, & Hisler, 2017). However, we view this not as a "complex interplay," as Marino described it, but as a relatively straightforward dislocation in which digital media displaces time once spent on face-to-face social interaction and sleep. How adolescents spend their leisure time has changed dramatically, which may have had significant impacts on their mental health. We disagree with Marino that "the amount of time spent online is not necessarily indicative of problematic use" (p. 455). The data in our article (Twenge, Joiner, Rogers, & Martin, 2018) show a fairly linear exposure-response curve; suicide-related outcomes steadily increase with daily hours of electronic device use. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2024 APA, all rights reserved)
